_meanings:
A particle of 
prohibition (rarely of negation) usually
joined with the Imperative; {#madvARi#}
{#mA kuru vizAdamanAdareRa#} <ls>Bv. 4. 41</ls>; also
({%a%}) with the Aorist, when the
augment {#a#} is dropped; {#pApe ratiM mA#}
{#kfTAH#} <ls>Bh. 2. 77</ls>; {#mA mUmuhat Kalu#} 
{#BavaMtamananyajanmA mA te malImasavikAraGanA#}
{#matirBUt#} <ls>Māl. 1. 32</ls>; the {#a#} is 
sometimes retained; {#mA nizAda pratizWAM#}
{#tvamagamaH SASvatIH samAH#} <ls>Rām.</ls> ({%b%}) the
Imperfect (the augment being
dropped here also); {#mA#} 
{#cEnamaBiBAzaTaH#} Rāma; ({%c%}) the Future, or
Potential mood, in the sense of
‘lest,’ ‘that not’; {#laGu etAM#} 
{#paritrAyasva mA kasyApi tapasvino haste#} 
{#patizyati#} <ls>Ś. 2</ls>; {#mA kaScinmamApyanarTo Baveta#} 

<ls>Pt. 5</ls>; {#mA nAma devyAH#} 
{#kimapyanizwamutpannaM Bavet#} <ls>K. 307</ls>; the Imperative
mood also is sometimes used for
the Potential; {#tvaratAmAryaputra etAM#} 
{#samASva sayituM mAsyA vikAro varDatAM#}  
<ls>M. 4.</ls> ({%d%}) the Present Participle when
a curse is implied; {#mA jIvanyaH#} 
{#parAvajYAduHKadagDopi jIvati#} <ls>Śi. 2. 45</ls>; or
({%e%}) with potential passive 
participles; {#mEvaM prArTyam#}. {#mA#} is sometimes
used without any verb; {#mA tAvat#}
‘oh ! do not (say or do) so’; {#mA#}
{#mEvaM; mA nAma rakziRaH#} <ls>Mk. 3.</ls> ‘may it
not be the police’; see under {#nAma#}.
Sometimes {#mA#} is followed by {#sma#} and
is used with the Aorist or 
Imperfect with the augment dropped,
and rarely with the potential mood;
{#klEbyaM mA sma gamaH pArTa#} <ls>Bg. 2. 3</ls>; {#mA#}
{#sma pratIpaM gamaH#} <ls>Ś. 4. 17</ls>; {#mAsma#} 
{#sImaMtinI kAcijjanayet putramIdfSam#}.
